9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 794, L.D. 1189, “An Act to Prohibit
10 Arrest and Detention for Civil Violations and Require an Attorney for the State to
11 Determine Whether to Charge a Class E Offense as a Civil Violation”
12 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'An Act to Allow an Attorney for the State to Determine Whether to Charge Certain
14 Class E Crimes as Civil Violations'
15 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
16 following:
17 'Sec. 1. 17-A MRSA §19-A is enacted to read:
18 §19-A. Election to charge Class E crime as civil violation
19 1. For purposes of this section, "eligible Class E crime" means any Class E crime,
20 except a Class E crime:
21 A. In Title 21-A; or
22 B. For which the defendant, if convicted, would be eligible for probation or subject to
23 a mandatory driver's license suspension.
24 2. The attorney for the State may elect to charge a defendant alleged to have committed
25 an eligible Class E crime with a civil violation instead of the eligible Class E crime unless
26 the defendant was arrested and objects to the substitution of a civil violation charge. In
27 deciding whether to make this election, the attorney for the State shall consider the severity
28 of the defendant's conduct, the impact of the conduct on the victim, any prior convictions
29 or adjudications entered against the defendant and any other factor relevant to whether a
30 criminal or civil sanction will best accomplish the purposes of the general sentencing
31 provisions in that particular case.
32 3. The determination by the attorney for the State under this section is not subject to
33 judicial review. For a person who is charged with and adjudicated as having committed a
34 civil violation under this section, a penalty of not more than $1,000 may be adjudged. The
Page 1 - 132LR2074(02)
